Course Project: Shiny Application and Reproducible Pitch

Maciej Komisarz

22.11.2019

Project Objective

The objective of this project was to:

  1. Write a shiny application with associated supporting documentation
  2. Deploy the application on Rstudio’s shiny server
  3. Share the application link by pasting it into the provided text box
  4. Share the server.R and ui.R code on github

What does the app do?

The application calculates the range of projectile motion, taking into consideration angle of throw and initial speed. As an output, it gives distance & height of projectile motion, and draws the trajectory line of motion.

Slide with R code

library(shiny)

shinyServer(function(input, output) {
        output$angle <- reactive({
            x <-input$Angle[1]
            })
        output$speed <- reactive({
            v <- input$Speed
            })
        output$height <- reactive({
            h <- (input$Speed^2*sin(input$Angle[1]*pi/180)^2)/(2*9.81)
            })
        output$val1 <- reactive({
            dst <- (input$Speed^2*sin(2*input$Angle[1]*pi/180))/9.81
            })
        output$plot1 <- renderPlot({
            p1 <-seq(0,((input$Speed^2*sin(2*input$Angle[1]*pi/180))/9.81),0.01)
            y <- tan(input$Angle[1]*pi/180)*p1-(9.81/(2*(input$Speed*cos(input$Angle[1]*pi/180))^2))*p1^2
            plot(p1,y,xlab="Range [m]",ylab = "Height [m]",
                xlim = c(0,((input$Speed^2*sin(2*input$Angle[1]*pi/180))/9.81)),
                ylim = c(0,(1.01*input$Speed^2*sin(input$Angle[1]*pi/180)^2)/(2*9.81)),
                col="blue")
           })
})

Example of trajectory plot

Below is shown a screenshot of the app window.
As it can be seen, app shows the following data:

  • selected angle of trajectory
  • selected speed of motion (in m/s)
  • calculated height of motion (in m)
  • calculated range of motion (in m)
  • plot of calculated trajectory

As output data are reactive, all shown values will be changing depending from input values.
